1
00:00:01,149 --> 00:00:02,549
<i>Previously on</i>
The Big Bang Theory...

2
00:00:03,266 --> 00:00:04,866
Sheldon, did you just figure out

3
00:00:04,868 --> 00:00:08,136
a method for synthesizing a new
stable super-heavy element?

4
00:00:08,257 --> 00:00:09,940
Did I?!

5
00:00:09,942 --> 00:00:11,208
Well, that can't be right.

6
00:00:11,210 --> 00:00:12,909
No one's ever done that before.

7
00:00:12,911 --> 00:00:14,377
Except me because I just did it!

8
00:00:14,379 --> 00:00:16,546
? Sheldon and his brain, yeah

9
00:00:16,548 --> 00:00:18,582
? Sheldon and his brain,
yeah! ?

10
00:00:18,584 --> 00:00:20,950
I've made a horrible mistake.

11
00:00:20,952 --> 00:00:22,052
What are you talking about?

12
00:00:22,054 --> 00:00:24,787
This table,
it's in square centimeters

13
00:00:24,789 --> 00:00:26,806
I read it as square meters.

14
00:00:26,808 --> 00:00:28,258
You know what that means?

15
00:00:28,260 --> 00:00:30,844
That Americans can't handle
the metric system?

16
00:00:32,430 --> 00:00:36,266
Amy, I was off
by a factor of 10,000.

17
00:00:36,268 --> 00:00:38,685
But the Chinese team
found the element.

18
00:00:38,687 --> 00:00:39,653
Yeah, well, they shouldn't have.

19
00:00:39,655 --> 00:00:41,605
My calculations were wrong.

20
00:00:41,607 --> 00:00:43,573
The greatest scientific
achievement of my life

21
00:00:43,575 --> 00:00:45,308
is based on a blunder.

22
00:00:45,310 --> 00:00:46,610
I'm not a genius.

23
00:00:46,612 --> 00:00:47,944
I'm a fraud.

24
00:00:47,946 --> 00:00:50,113
You know, Sheldon,
in neuroscience,

25
00:00:50,115 --> 00:00:52,815
we're forever finding something
in one part of the brain

26
00:00:52,817 --> 00:00:54,284
that we thought was
someplace else.

27
00:00:54,286 --> 00:00:56,986
Oh, great, now I'm
worse than a fraud.

28
00:00:56,988 --> 00:00:59,155
I'm practically a biologist.
someplace else.

29
00:01:01,759 --> 00:01:04,261
This is <i>Science Friday.</i>
I'm Ira Flatow.

30
00:01:04,263 --> 00:01:07,597
My guest today is responsible
for the discovery of the first

31
00:01:07,599 --> 00:01:10,166
stable super-heavy element.

32
00:01:10,168 --> 00:01:11,685
Welcome, Dr. Sheldon Cooper.

33
00:01:11,687 --> 00:01:13,436
Thank you.

34
00:01:13,438 --> 00:01:15,021
Uh, the university
made me come here.

35
00:01:15,023 --> 00:01:16,506
I didn't want to.

36
00:01:17,325 --> 00:01:20,360
Uh, big fan of the show.

37
00:01:20,362 --> 00:01:23,346
So, I understand
that you actually discovered

38
00:01:23,348 --> 00:01:25,532
this element by mistake.

39
00:01:27,486 --> 00:01:29,319
Yes.

40
00:01:29,321 --> 00:01:32,372
And some people in the science
community are calling it

41
00:01:32,374 --> 00:01:34,357
"The Wonder Blunder."

42
00:01:34,359 --> 00:01:36,025
Who? Give me their names.

43
00:01:36,027 --> 00:01:37,911
I bet it's Wolowitz.

44
00:01:37,913 --> 00:01:40,297
It's just such
a fascinating story.

45
00:01:40,299 --> 00:01:41,831
Your calculations are way off,

46
00:01:41,833 --> 00:01:44,200
but they find
the element anyway.

47
00:01:44,202 --> 00:01:46,503
It's like misreading
a treasure map

48
00:01:46,505 --> 00:01:48,922
and still finding the treasure.

49
00:01:48,924 --> 00:01:50,924
Can we talk
about something else?

50
00:01:50,926 --> 00:01:53,510
Do you know that I yodel?

51
00:01:55,846 --> 00:01:57,230
That's interesting,
but this could be taking you

52
00:01:57,232 --> 00:01:59,983
down the path
toward a Nobel Prize.

53
00:01:59,985 --> 00:02:01,351
And in chemistry, no less.

54
00:02:01,353 --> 00:02:03,503
And wouldn't
that be unusual?

55
00:02:03,505 --> 00:02:05,855
Because you're a physicist.

56
00:02:05,857 --> 00:02:08,158
Yes, yes, I'd be a physicist
with a Nobel in chemistry.

57
00:02:08,160 --> 00:02:10,360
Everyone laugh
at the circus freak.

58
00:02:11,612 --> 00:02:14,164
You know, I don't need to sit
here and take this, Flatow.

59
00:02:14,166 --> 00:02:16,499
It is because of bullies
like you,

60
00:02:16,501 --> 00:02:18,201
every day
more and more Americans

61
00:02:18,203 --> 00:02:20,704
are making the switch
to television.

62
00:02:21,789 --> 00:02:25,425
? Our whole universe
was in a hot, dense state ?

63
00:02:25,427 --> 00:02:28,762
? Then nearly 14 billion years
ago expansion started... Wait! ?

64
00:02:28,764 --> 00:02:30,397
? The Earth ban to cool

65
00:02:30,399 --> 00:02:32,932
? The autotrophs began to drool,
Neanderthals developed tools ?

66
00:02:32,934 --> 00:02:35,602
? We built the Wall
? <i>We built the pyramids</i> ?

67
00:02:35,604 --> 00:02:38,271
? Math, Science, History,
unraveling the mystery ?

68
00:02:38,273 --> 00:02:40,190
? That all started
with a big bang ?

69
00:02:40,192 --> 00:02:42,142
? <i>Bang!</i> ?

70
00:02:42,149 --> 00:02:46,149
<font color=#00FF00>? The Big Bang Theory 7x10 ?</font>
<font color=#00FFFF>The Discovery Dissipation</font>
